      "writtenOn": "2018-09-17T15:56:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Q: So if the test that stopped a service failed mid-way, how does the next test ensure that service is up? This seems to conflict with the de-init advice above. I can blindly follow this rule, but I don\u0027t really understand why it\u0027s different.",
      "revId": "713f326953534ea42cb89eddbbb2664bcf8751b7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7f683354_61d36168",
        "filename": "docs/writing_tests.md",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 147,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000042
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-17T16:16:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i added another paragraph here that mentions \u0027defer\u0027, which can help -- a failing test should still try to fix things before it goes.\n\nin practice, i think my stance here is, \"assume you\u0027re getting a reasonable environment when your test starts, but don\u0027t make assumptions about chrome\u0027s initial state. similarly, try to leave the system in a reasonable state, but don\u0027t worry about what chrome is doing when you go.\" i\u0027ve also stated that explicitly now.",
      "parentUuid": "48af7bd7_52efa271",
      "revId": "713f326953534ea42cb89eddbbb2664bcf8751b7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
